  "prompt": "How can the Shia Kalma qualify for Shahdah as it distorts the fundamental word of Allah (SWT) by modifying the Tayyibah kalimat a\u1e6d-\u1e6daiyibah?",
  "response": "The Shahadah is the Islamic declaration of faith, proclaiming the oneness of Allah and the prophethood of Muhammad. The Sunni Shahadah is typically recited as:\n\n*\"Ashhadu an la ilaha illallah, wa ashhadu anna Muhammadan rasulullah\"*  \n(\"I bear witness that there is no god but Allah, and I bear witness that Muhammad is the messenger of Allah\").\n\nShia Muslims, particularly those of the Twelver tradition, often include an additional phrase in their declaration:\n\n*\"Ashhadu an la ilaha illallah, wa ashhadu anna Muhammadan rasulullah, wa ashhadu anna Aliyyan waliyyullah\"*  \n(\"I bear witness that there is no god but Allah, and I bear witness that Muhammad is the messenger of Allah, and I bear witness that Ali is the wali (friend, guardian) of Allah\").\n\nThe inclusion of \"Aliyyan waliyyullah\" reflects the Shia belief in the special status of Ali, the cousin and son-in-law of Muhammad, and the first Imam in Shia Islam. This variation underscores their theological framework and emphasis on the role of the Imams.\n\nFrom a theological perspective:\n\n1. **Sunni View**: Many Sunni scholars and adherents might argue that the addition distorts the fundamental declaration of faith by introducing elements not present in the original Shahadah as taught by the Prophet Muhammad. They emphasize the importance of maintaining the purity of the Shahadah as it is foundational to Islamic belief and practice.\n\n2. **Shia Perspective**: Shia scholars and adherents generally argue that the addition does not distort the Shahadah but rather complements it by acknowledging the rightful succession of leadership after Muhammad. They believe that Ali and the subsequent Imams are divinely appointed leaders who provide guidance in understanding and implementing the teachings of Islam.\n\nUltimately, the difference in the Shahadah stems from theological and historical differences between Sunni and Shia Islam. Each tradition has its own interpretations and practices that are deeply rooted in their understanding of Islamic teachings and history.\n\nIt's important to approach such differences with respect and understanding, recognizing that diverse interpretations exist within the broader Islamic tradition. Dialogue and study can help bridge gaps and foster mutual respect among Muslims of different sects.",
